This paper is about training Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) for natural language generation, which falls under the category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). The paper also discusses techniques such as large batch sizes and discriminator regularization, which are commonly used in machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper mentions challenges with gradient estimation and optimization instability, which are also relevant to neural networks (cs.NE). Finally, the paper compares the performance of the proposed model to traditional language models, which may involve image processing techniques (cs.CV) for evaluating the quality and diversity of generated samples.
